{{italic title}}
'''''Blyew v. United States''''' was a case heard before the [[U.S. Supreme Court]] in April 1872 addressing the [[Civil rights in the United States|civil rights]] of [[African Americans]], as well as [[states' rights]] issues. The case involved the testimony of a dying man who identified his attackers and the testimony of other African American victims of an attack with an axe. [[Kentucky]] [[State law (United States)|state law]] prohibited the testimony of a "Negro" against a white man and barred African Americans from serving on juries. After the attackers were convicted in [[Federal judiciary of the United States|Federal court]], the State of Kentucky appealed the case to the Supreme Court citing States Rights in defense of its laws prohibitting African Americans from testifying against Whites. The case was a test of the [[Civil Rights Act of 1866]]. The Supreme Court ruled that victims were not entitled to protection from the state law because word "affected" in the law did not apply to victims of crimes who are not defendants in a case.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NM_rf6TndMsC&pg=PA79|title=Shades of Freedom: Racial Politics and Presumptions of the American Legal Process|first=A. Leon |last=Higginbotham Jr |pages=79-80 |year=1998|publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=0-19-512288-7}}</ref> [[Noah Swayne]] (the first [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] appointed to the Supreme Court) and [[Joseph Bradley]] dissented.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-0AoCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA52 |page=52|title=The Kentucky African American Encyclopedia|first1=Gerald L.|last1=Smith|first2=Karen Cotton|last2=McDaniel|first3=John A.|last3=Hardin|year=2015|publisher=University Press of Kentucky |isbn=978-0-8131-6066-5}}</ref> The civil rights legislation was subsequently modified and comments in the dissent are noted for putting forth a group right to the adequate protection of the law.<ref>{{cite web |title=Blyew v. United States 80 U.S. 581 (1872) |work=Encyclopedia of the American Constitution |url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/politics/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/blyew-v-united-states-80-us-581-1872 |accessdate=2018-03-07}}</ref> Justice [[William Strong (Pennsylvania judge)|William Strong]] wrote that any case involving an African American witness could be brought to a Federal Court if the court had ruled for the victims and upheld the right of African Americans to testify in court.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OmBVwP4-LScC&pg=PA20 |title=The Supreme Court's Retreat from Reconstruction: A Distortion of Constitutional Jurisprudence|first=Frank J. |last=Scaturro |page=20 |year=2000 |isbn=0-313-31105-6 |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group}}</ref>

