{{Infobox room |name = Hercules Drawing Room {{Nowrap|(''{{lang|fr|{{Noitalics|Salon d'Hercule}}}}'')}} |image = Grande salle chateau de versailles.jpg |caption = Created 1724–1736 by [[Robert de Cotte]], [[Jacques Gabriel]], [[Antoine Vassé]], and [[Claude&nbsp;Tarlé]] |building = [[Palace of Versailles]] |location = |country = France |coordinates = {{Coord|48.80497|2.12172|type:landmark_region:FR_scale:1000|display=inline, title}} |purpose = |namedfor = [[Hercules]] }}
The '''Salon d'Hercule''' (also known as the '''Hercules Salon''' or the '''Hercules Drawing Room''') is on the [[first floor]] of the [[Château de Versailles]] and connects the [[Royal Chapel of Versailles|Royal Chapel]] in the North Wing of the château with the ''[[grand appartement du roi]]''.
==Description== Originally, the fourth and penultimate chapel, the ''salon d’Hercule'' occupies the tribune level of this chapel. Initially called the ''nouveau salon près de la chapelle'' (new salon near the chapel) when the room was started in 1710 by [[Robert de Cotte]] for [[Louis XIV]]. However, with the death of [[Louis XIV]] in 1715 the project was postponed (Verlet, 321).
Beginning in 1724, work on the ''salon d’Hercule'' recommenced. [[Louis XV]] commissioned architect [[Jacques Gabriel]], ''marbrier'' [[Claude-Félix Tarlé]], and sculptors [[Jacques Verberckt]] and [[François-Antoine Vassé]] to complete the room (Verlet, 321).
The room was completed in 1736 with the ceiling painting ''Apothéose d’Hercule'' (''Apotheosis of Hercules'') by [[François Le Moyne]], which gave the room its present name (Verlet, 322).
There are only two other paintings decorating this room, both of which are by [[Paolo Veronese|Veronese]]. Above the fireplace is the artist’s ''Rebecca at the Well''; on the opposite wall forming a pendant is the famed ''Feast in the House of Simon'' (Verlet, 322). [[Louis XIV]] received the latter painting as a [[diplomatic gift]] from the Republic of Venice in 1664. Owing to the size of the work – 4.5 meters high by 9.7 meters long – the painting was displayed in the ''[[galerie d’Apollon]]'' of the [[Louvre]]. It was installed in ''salon d’Hercule'' in 1730 where it remained until 1832 at which time it was transferred to the [[Louvre]]. In 1961 the ''Feast in the House of Simon'' was returned to the ''salon d’Hercule.'' In 1994, under the aegis of the Société des amis de Versailles and BNP the painting was restored.<ref>[http://www.amisdeversailles.com/chateau-de-versailles-restauration-le-repas-chez-simon-par-veronese.html Société des amis de Versailles] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081120185429/http://www.amisdeversailles.com/chateau-de-versailles-restauration-le-repas-chez-simon-par-veronese.html |date=2008-11-20 }}</ref>
During the reign of [[Louis XV]] the room served as a ball room as the king felt the [[salon de Mars]] was too small and the ''[[Hall of Mirrors (Palace of Versailles)|galerie des glaces]]'' was too large. The inaugural ball held in the ''salon d’Hercule'' was on 26 January 1739 to celebrate the marriage of [[Louis XV|Louis XV’s]] eldest daughter [[Princess Louise-Élisabeth of France|Marie Louise-Élisabeth]] with [[Philip, Duke of Parma|Infante Filipe of Spain]] (Luynes, 335-345); and the wedding dinner ''au grand courvert'' of the [[Louis Philippe d'Orléans (1747-1793)|duc de Chartres]] on 5 January 1769 (Verlet, 323). After the destruction of the ''[[escalier des ambassadeurs]]'' in 1752, [[Louis XV]] planned for the ''salon d’Hercule'' to be the landing for a new staircase for the château (Verlet, 323).
During the reign of [[Louis XVI]] the ''salon d’Hercule'' served for diplomatic functions such as the embassy sent by the bey of Tunis (January 1777); the receptions of the representatives of the Three Estates of the [[French States-General|Estates-General]] (May 1789); and, the reception of the embassy of the sultan [[Mysore]] (September 1778) (Verlet, 555).
