[[File:V&A Spiral.jpg|thumb|right|Architect's impression of The Spiral]]
The '''Victoria and Albert Museum Spiral''' (or '''V&A Spiral''', or '''The Spiral''') was a proposed extension to the 19th-century London building which houses the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]], the world's largest museum of decorative arts. It was designed by [[Daniel Libeskind]] and the designer, artist, and writer, [[Cecil Balmond]]. The museum chose the design over seven others in competition in 1996 but, after much controversy and failing three times to attract the necessary funding, the project was abandoned in 2004.{{ref supports2|
<ref name=G2011>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2011/mar/03/v-and-a-spiral-seven-designs-gallery|title=The V&A goes underground with shortlisted designs for new gallery|author=Jonathan Glancey|work=the Guardian|accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref>
|"a proposed extension to a 19th century London building that is home to the world's largest museum of decorative arts ... designed by Daniel Libeskind, and the designer, artist, and writer, Cecil Balmond."}}{{ref supports2
|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/07/29/arts/a-blow-perhaps-fatal-for-libeskind-s-spiral-in-london.html|title=A Blow, Perhaps Fatal, for Libeskind's Spiral in London|date=29 July 2004|work=nytimes.com|accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref>
|"The museum chose the design over seven others in competition in 1996, but after much controversy and failing three times to attract the necessary funding the project was abandoned ..."}}{{ref supports2
|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2004/sep/18/urbandesign.arts|title=No go for V&A's Spiral extension - Society - The Guardian|author=Jonathan Glancey|work=the Guardian|accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref>
|"in 2004."}}

When the design was chosen in 1996, Libeskind was relatively unknown, but in 1999 he won international acclaim for the [[Jewish Museum, Berlin|Jewish Museum in Berlin]], and his master plan for the [[World Trade Center site]] in New York has made him a household name there.{{ref supports2
